Clustering App-store reviews¶

The goal of this project is to experiment with clusetring customer reviews from App-store. I wanted to pick some controlversial app, so my choice fell on Tinder, which is a dating app. Clustering text data is very challenging task, however rewarding if done rightly. Clustering app reviews can help to find common themes of customer feedback, identify pain points for the users, and improve the app.

In this excersise, I want to group the reviews which have common themes or sentimentes, and make sure that reviews different from each other are in separate groups. I chose to work on Title of the reviews, rather then reviews themselves as it showed better clusetring quality.

4. Text pre-processing¶

To make sure review titles are suitable for clustering, text pre-processing is a must. Noise in text data negatively impacts quality of clustering.
Text pre-processing steps invlove:

  • making letters lowercase
  • remove signs and punctuations
  • tokenizing text (breaking down text into individual words)
  • remove stop words from the text
In [313]:
#nltk.download('punkt')
#nltk.download('stopwords')


def text_pre_process(text):

    text = text.lower()
    text = text.translate(str.maketrans("", "", string.punctuation))
    text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', text)
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(text)
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words("english"))
    tokens = [word for word in tokens if word not in stop_words]
    text = " ".join(tokens)
    return text

data["title"] = data["title"].apply(text_pre_process)

5. Vectorizing¶

If we want to apply machine learning algorithms on text data (sequance of words), it is necesasary to vectorize our data - transform text into numerical representaions. As backbone of each clusetring method is to calculate similarity between datapoints, it can`t be done directly on text data.


For vectorizing text data, there are two main vectorization methods to use:


1. CountVectorizer

It creates a bag-of-words representation of the text data, where each dimension of the vector represents a word, and the value in each dimension represents the number of times that word appears in the document.


2. TF-IDF

It creates a representation where each dimension of the vector represents a word, and the value in each dimension represents the relative importance of that word in the document with respect to all documents in the corpus.


My choice

Intuitively, I firstly picked TF-IDF method, as it is more sophisticated and is able to identify relative importance of a word, not only frequency in the document as in case of CountVectoriser. However to my surprise, CountVectorizer gave much better results in terms of both a) clustering quality measures - Silhouette and CalinskiHarabasz scores and b) results made more sense, which will be discussed later on, so I sticked to a simpler method.

Here we see that sparse matrix object is created as a result

6. Find optimal number of clusters¶

This can be done in a few ways. Two most commonly used are Elbow Method and Silhouette score.

1. Elbow Method</br>

  • Within-cluster sum of squares (WCSS) are being plotted against the number of clusters.
  • Then it finds the "elbow" point, where the WCSS starts to decrease at a slower rate
  • So adding more clusters does not significantly reduce the WCSS hence does not improve qulaity of clustering.
  • The number of clusters corresponding to the elbow point is considered the optimal number of clusters.

It is rather heruistic approach. It is not most optimal way to find a good k, as there can be multiple elbows in the plot or it is not clearly visible. I used fancy Yellowbrick library, where quality scores are calculated under the hook, and it suggets optimal values. In our case the plot looks a bit confusing, and is suggesting 5 clusters.

Let`s try a more sophisticated method

In [316]:

visualizer.fit(review_vectors.toarray())
visualizer.show()

2. Silhouete score</br>

The silhouette score is a metric used to evaluate the quality of clustering in unsupervised learning. It measures the similarity of an object to its own cluster compared to other clusters.

For each sample in the data, the SS is calculated like that:

  • Computes intra-cluster similarity, which is an average distance between the sample and all other points in its own cluster
  • Computes inter-cluster separation, which is the average distance of the sample vs. all other points in the closest other cluster.
  • SS for the sample is difference between the inter-cluster separation and the intra-cluster similarity, divided by the maximum of these two values:

SS = (inter_cluster_separation - intra_cluster_similarity) / max(inter_cluster_separation, intra_cluster_similarity)

For a set of samples, it is the average of the silhouette scores of all the samples. The silhouette score ranges from -1 to 1:

  • 1: perfect clustering
  • 0: overlapping clusters
  • -1: poor clustering
In [318]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans


range_n_clusters = range(2, 15)


silhouette_scores = []


for n_clusters in range_n_clusters:
  
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)
    kmeans.fit(review_vectors)
    

    silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(review_vectors, kmeans.labels_)
 
    silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_avg)

plt.plot(range_n_clusters, silhouette_scores)
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.show()
In [321]:
model = KMeans(n_clusters=5)


model.fit(review_vectors.toarray())


visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(model, colors='yellowbrick')


visualizer.fit(review_vectors.toarray())


visualizer.show()
Out[321]:
<AxesSubplot: title={'center': 'Silhouette Plot of KMeans Clustering for 3000 Samples in 5 Centers'}, xlabel='silhouette coefficient values', ylabel='cluster label'>

From Silhouette analysis, based on the average scores for cluster range 1-15, we can conclude that clusters formed are not of the best quality. Score around 0.1 tells us that clusetrs can be formed,but they are somewhat overlapping. However it is not as bad as -1, or a negative number, and given challenges of clusetring text data, we can still look at the results for learning purposes.

I decided to choose k as 5, given Elbow Method & Silhouette score results. I didn`t go for higher k, as in SS plot, improvement from k=5 to bigger k is not significant, plus our sample size = 3000 is not so large for the headlines.

Results¶

I used WorldCloud library to visualize the results of clusetring to see if we can gather common themes based on word frequency in each cluster.

As we can observe, reviews are mostly negative and form 5 themes:


cluster 1: Complains on account ban + scamming
cluster 4: Tinder is the worst dating app
cluster 5: Complaints about customer service
cluster 3: Tinder is a waste of time and money
cluster 2: Account wrongfully banned

** Finally, I changed vectorizer method from CountVectorizer to TF-IDF. Even though it reduces the silhouette score, it gives cleaner results in terms of cluster presentation. I assume it happens as less important words get removed from the cloud.

In [332]:
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
review_vectors = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=5)
kmeans.fit(review_vectors)


labels = kmeans.labels_

for i in range(5):
    cluster_reviews = [reviews[j] for j in range(len(reviews)) if labels[j] == i]
    text = ' '.join(cluster_reviews)
    wordcloud = WordCloud().generate(text)
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.title("Cluster {}".format(i))
    plt.show()
    
    
cluster_sizes = np.unique(labels, return_counts=True)[1]


plt.bar(np.arange(len(cluster_sizes)), cluster_sizes)
plt.xlabel("Cluster")
plt.ylabel("Size")
plt.show()

Conclusion¶

After this experiment, I can conclude that clustering text data is a challenging task, involving a lot of text pre-processing. Data of this type contains much more noise and dimensions, hence it is hard to apply common dimension reduction techniques on this type. Cluster sizes are evidently uneqal with the first cluster being much larger than others. I tried several techniques to fix that, including different vectorization method, trying various distance metrics good specifically for text such as Coisine distance, however it did not make clusetrs moge equal in size. Incraesing number of clusetrs did help, but they were much more overlapping and situation with 1 very large cluster vs other smaller persisted. Despite qulaity measure scores being not so ideal and cluster size being uneven, I still think this experiment was valuable as it allowed to extract common themes from app-store reviews and I learned a lot on the way.
